<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12033e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12033e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12033e"> 33(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Lycaenion Daphnis &amp; Chloe</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il est impressionnant, ce rocher sauvage, avec son front chauve et ses flancs broussailleux, sur lesquels court, r&eacute;guli&egrave;re et noir&acirc;tre, la laisse des eaux. Tombelaine fut, para&icirc;t-il, dans la pr&eacute;histoire, le si&egrave;ge d&apos;un coll&egrave;ge de druidesses, de tr&egrave;s petite vertu, s&apos;il faut en croire les pudibonds chroniqueurs du Mont- Saint-Michel. Ces dames avaient, disait-on, la sp&eacute;cialit&eacute; de donner &agrave; la jeunesse certaines le&ccedil;ons de choses que la charmante nymphe Lyc&eacute;nion d&eacute;voila au na&iuml;f Daphnis, se consumant pour Chlo&euml;. <br><font color="green">[It is impressive, this wild rock, with its bare front and its bushy flanks on which runs, regular and blackish, la laissa des eaux. Tombelaine was, it seems, in prehistory the seat of a college of druidesses, of small virtue, if we are to believe the prudish chroniclers of Mont-Saint-Michel. These ladies were in the habit, it was said, of giving to youngsters the same kind of lessons that the charming nymph Lyc&eacute;nion gave to the simple Daphnis, who was consumed by desire for Chlo&euml;.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 219</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
